english:
  title: The Fisherman's Village
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Fisherman's Village is the chosen name of my friend Kong Baekgong. Though we were born in the same year, his birthday comes after mine, so I call myself his elder. His bearing and character are open and bright, worthy of love and friendship. He passed the great examination and rose to a generous position of rank, wearing official ribbons and seals, keeping his brush always at his cap, and custodian of the imperial seal. Yet despite people's great expectations for his advancement, he maintains a serene attachment to the pleasures of rivers and lakes. When inspiration stirs, he sings the Fisherman's Songs, his voice so clear and resonant that it seems to fill heaven and earth. It is as if one hears Zengzi singing the Odes of Shang—the listener's heart becomes lost in those distant waters. This comes from his mind being free of private desires, transcendent above material things, so that what emerges in his voice carries such power.

    Once he said to me: "My heart dwells in the fisherman's way. Do you know the fisherman's joy? The Grand Duke of the East was a sage, yet I dare not presume to match his fate. Yan Ziling was a worthy, yet I dare not aspire to his purity. With children and companions, befriending gulls and herons, sometimes grasping a fishing rod, sometimes rowing a lonely boat, rising and falling with the tide, going where it leads—when the sand is clean we moor our line, when the mountains are fair we drift through their midst. We grill fresh catch and toast with wine cups.

    When day falls and the moon rises, wind gentle and waves still, we recline against the boat and whistle long into the night, strike the mast and sing in full voice. We raise the white waters and pierce the clear light, soaring—soaring as if riding the legendary raft to the heavens themselves.

    Or when river mists grow thick and dark fog descends, we don our cloaks and cast our nets—scales gleaming like gold, tails white as jade, fish leaping and writhing in delight that fills both eye and heart.

    When night deepens and clouds darken the sky, all directions blur into vastness. The fisherman's lamp glimmers faintly; rain patters on the woven canopy—soft then swift, sounds cold and mournful. Lying in the boat, spirit wanders through the empty immensity. We remember Cangwu, mourn those lost in the Xiang—and find ourselves touched by time, seized by endless reflection.

    When flowers bloom on both banks, the body dwells within a painting. When rains cease and cold pools remain, the boat glides as through a mirror. When summer's scorching heat descends, a breeze stirs the willow-lined fishing bank. When winter snow flies through heaven, we cast our line alone in the freezing river. Through all four seasons the fisherman's joy never departs.

    Those who gain rank through worldly success cling pathetically to glory, yet I am at peace with my lot. Those poor who fish for livelihood calculate profit narrowly, yet I delight in simple freedom. I entrust ascent and descent to fate, advance and retreat to the season alone. I regard wealth and rank as passing clouds, cast away fame like worn-out shoes. Thus do I wander freely beyond the bonds of form and body. How could this compare to those who chase the times and fish for fame, drowning in the waters of office, courting profit at the cost of life, stumbling willingly into the abyss?

    This is why, though my body wears official rank, my spirit dwells by rivers and lakes—why I ever entrust myself to song. What do you make of this?"

    Hearing his words, I was filled with joy. So I have written this record to send him, and also that I might examine myself by it.

    In the seventh month of the Yizhou year of Hongwu.
  footnotes:
    - 'Kong Baekong (孔伯共): A historical figure from the early Joseon period, known for his scholarly achievement and official service despite his attachment to the ideals of reclusion and natural freedom.'
    - 'The Fisherman''s Songs (漁父詞): References to classical poetry celebrating the fisherman''s life as a symbol of freedom and detachment from worldly ambitions.'
    - 'Grand Duke of the East and Yan Ziling: Historical figures—Lü Shang who served as advisor and Yan Ziling who refused court service—representing different approaches to governance and reclusion.'
    - 'Cangwu and the Xiang River: Allusions to legendary sage-kings and tragic exile, evoking melancholy reflection on time''s passage and human suffering.'
    - 'Yizhou year of Hongwu: This text was written during the Hongwu reign period of the Ming Dynasty (likely 1385 C.E.).'
